It is based on the principles of plasmon excitation and emission of light, and is particularly useful for studying samples that are not easily characterizable by other methods such as X-ray diffraction or electron microscopy. Raman spectroscopy is widely used in fields such as materials science, physics, chemistry, biology, and environmental science.It is a technique in which a sample is exposed to a laser beam, which excites the matter in the sample to a higher energy state. This is followed by a decay of the excited matter, which can emit light at frequencies other than those of the incident laser beam. The emitted light is then detected by a photodetector and analyzed spectroscopically to obtain information about the molecular composition and properties of the sample.One of the main advantages of Raman spectroscopy is its non-destructive nature, which makes it suitable for studying samples in situ and without altering their properties. The technique is also relatively simple to operate and can be applied to a wide variety of samples, including solids, liquids, gases, and biological macromolecules.	2-None	False
